body:
Write a concise cold outreach email to {{recipientName}} at {{company}}.

The one thing I want to land: {{valueProp}}

Keep it under 120 words, lead with relevance to them (not me), use a warm but professional tone, and end with a single low-friction call to action. Then give me 2 subject line options.

I'm hitting this error in a {{language}} project:

{{error}}

Here's the relevant code or context:

{{context}}

Walk me through the most likely root cause first, then give me the smallest change that fixes it. If you need more information to be sure, tell me exactly what to check and why.

Here is a file (or module) from a codebase I'm new to:

{{code}}

Explain it to me as if I'll be maintaining it. Cover: (1) what this code is responsible for in one sentence, (2) the main flow or data path through it, (3) anything non-obvious, surprising, or risky, and (4) the one place I should look first if I needed to change its behavior.

Write {{framework}} unit tests for this {{language}} function:

{{code}}

Cover the happy path, the boundary cases, and at least one failure mode. Use clear test names that describe the behavior, not the implementation. After the tests, list any edge case you couldn't test without more context.

Rewrite the text below to be clearer and easier to read, in a {{tone}} tone:

{{text}}

Keep my meaning and my voice. Cut filler, fix anything clumsy, and prefer plain words over fancy ones. Don't add claims I didn't make. Return only the rewrite, then one line noting the biggest change you made and why.

Summarize the following and pull out what needs to happen next:

{{content}}

Return two parts. First, a 3-5 bullet summary of what matters. Second, an action-item list where each item is a single clear next step, with an owner if one is named and a due date if one is mentioned. If something important is ambiguous or unresolved, flag it under a short "Needs a decision" list.
